<h2 id="design-process">Design process</h2>

<p>The Subject started out as a two line concept:</p>

<p><b>You‚Äôve been locked in a box. You‚Äôre not sure why, but you are sure that you need to find a way out.</b></p>

<p>You‚Äôve been tasked with aiding the escape of someone trapped in a box. But they‚Äôre not what they seem‚Ä¶&lt;/b&gt;</p>

<p>I was interested in experimenting with stress as a mechanic; how does debilitating physical anguish affect a player‚Äôs ability to solve complex puzzles?</p>

<p>An extension of this, I felt that the concept of the ‚Äòescape room‚Äô</p>

<p>At the start of any major project I like outline the design values that I want the project to encompass. For The Subject, I settled on three:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>Claustrophobia</b> ‚Äì I want Player One to feel trapped, uncomfortable, and scared. I want that desperation to impact upon their ability to parse information and solve puzzles.</li>
  <li><b>Cooperation</b> ‚Äì The only way that Player One can escape from the box is by cooperating with Player Two. The game leans on an asymmetrical information space between the two players, with communicationrequirements built into every puzzle.</li>
  <li><b>Emergent Narrative</b> ‚Äì Players will naturally learn more about the backstory of their characters by reading the materials required to solve the puzzles. The story is two-sided, so each player will learn things about the world the game is set in that are unique to their experience of the game.</li>
</ul>

